WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:81.000
Let's lock in the four pillars of Part 1. First, the Gap: traditional clinical training creates expert practitioners, but not necessarily system innovators — the skills that make a great clinician aren't the same ones that redesign a broken system. Second, the Mission: to move from being an employee within the system to an innovation leader who shapes it — a designer who bridges the gap between current limitations and future possibilities. Third, the Journey: a three-waypoint progression — identifying opportunities, then designing and pitching solutions, then driving lasting, measurable impact — and your deliverables are a tangible playbook and an executive one-pager. And fourth, the Mindset: success takes agility, first-principles thinking, psychological safety, and the willingness to embrace intelligent failure — treating every setback as signal, not verdict. With that, you're ready to transition from a clinical tactician to a systemic intrapreneur. Up next, in Part 2 — Building the Solution: Design, Plan, and Pitch — we'll put this mindset to work and learn how to properly diagnose and frame the root cause of a problem. Bring the real-world clinical frictions you've identified with you.
